  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Flood overlays are one of the more misunderstood aspects of selling property in Brisbane. Many sellers either underestimate what they need to disclose or assume that an overlay automatically destroys their sale prospects. The reality is more nuanced. What matters is understanding exactly what your overlay means, what buyers can legitimately ask about it, and how to present the property in a way that is transparent, accurate, and commercially sensible.</p>

      <p>Brisbane City Council manages flood mapping and overlay categories through its City Plan. Properties in flood-affected or flood-constrained areas will show overlay information on the property's development conditions, which are accessible through Council's property lookup tools and through a standard REIQ contract search. As a seller, you cannot control whether the overlay exists, but you can control how well you understand it and how clearly you communicate about it.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The different overlay categories</h2>
      <p>Brisbane City Council's flood overlay is divided into several categories, each reflecting a different flood risk scenario.</p>

      <p>The Creek Flood Overlay applies to properties within areas subject to flooding from local creek systems. This includes waterways like Norman Creek, Bulimba Creek, and Kedron Brook, which flow through the inner east and northern suburbs. Creek flooding is often more localised and can affect properties well upstream of the Brisbane River.</p>

      <p>The River Flood Overlay applies to properties within the modelled inundation area for the Brisbane River, based on flood events of various annual exceedance probabilities. The most commonly referenced benchmark is the 1% AEP event (sometimes called the 1-in-100-year flood), though more extreme events are also modelled.</p>

      <p>The Overland Flow Path Overlay identifies areas where stormwater runoff concentrates and flows across land during heavy rainfall, separate from river or creek flooding. This overlay affects a broader range of properties and does not necessarily mean a property has flooded or is at high risk of flooding from a river event.</p>

      <p>It is worth noting that the overlays are modelling tools, not records of actual flood history. A property can sit within a flood overlay area and have never experienced inundation, depending on its specific elevation, the extent of the flood event modelled, and local drainage conditions. Conversely, a property outside the overlay can still experience flooding in extreme events. The overlay tells you about modelled risk at a population level, not the specific historical experience of your property.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Disclosure obligations for Queensland sellers</h2>
      <p>Under Queensland property law, sellers have obligations under both the Property Occupations Act 2014 and the standard REIQ contract to disclose material facts that a buyer could not reasonably discover for themselves. Flood overlay status is typically discoverable through a standard property search, but the actual flood history of a property, if the seller has knowledge of it, is a different matter.</p>

      <p>If you are aware that the property has experienced inundation during your ownership, that is information you should disclose. Non-disclosure of a known material defect or adverse fact can expose you to claims from the buyer after settlement. Your conveyancer or solicitor should walk you through your specific obligations based on the property's circumstances. This is not an area to navigate without proper legal advice.</p>

      <p>Council flood searches, which are typically ordered by the buyer's conveyancer as part of due diligence, will return the property's overlay status and any recorded flood event history in Council's systems. These searches are standard practice. Buyers purchasing in Brisbane's inner east, particularly in low-lying suburbs adjacent to creeks or the river, are generally well-informed about flood risk and expect to see this information.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Effect on buyer pool and price</h2>
      <p>A flood overlay does affect the buyer pool, but the extent of that effect depends heavily on the specific overlay type, the property's actual flood history, its elevation relative to the overlay, and the buyer's personal risk tolerance and intended use.</p>

      <p>Owner-occupiers buying in creek-adjacent suburbs like Bulimba, Hawthorne, and Norman Park are generally aware of the flood risk context and have already self-selected for it. Many buyers in these suburbs are drawn precisely because of the creek-side lifestyle, and they factor flood risk into their decision rather than being shocked by it. A well-elevated property on a creek-side street with no history of inundation, even if it sits within a modelled flood area, will still attract strong competition from buyers who have done their research.</p>

      <p>The buyer pool does narrow when a property has a documented flood history, particularly if the flooding caused significant damage or required insurance claims. In those cases, finance can also become more difficult: some lenders apply stricter lending criteria or require specialist insurance products for properties with a flood claim history, which can affect a buyer's borrowing capacity or increase their holding costs materially.</p>

      <p>On price, the honest assessment is that an overlay alone, without a history of actual inundation, tends to have a modest effect on comparable sales. Properties with a known flood history typically sell at a discount compared to structurally equivalent properties with no flood history, and the size of that discount varies with how recent and severe the flooding was, what remediation was done, and whether insurance is readily available at standard rates.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How to present your property honestly</h2>
      <p>The right approach is transparent, specific, and supported by documentation. If your property sits within a flood overlay but has not flooded, say so clearly and be prepared to explain why: whether it is elevation, the specific overlay type, or local drainage. If Council has updated its flood modelling since 2011 or 2022 and your property's overlay status has changed, that is worth explaining to buyers.</p>

      <p>If the property has flooded, document what happened, what remediation was done, what it cost, and what has changed since. Buyers are more confident when they understand the scope of what occurred than when they are left to imagine the worst. Relevant documents include council flood reports, insurance correspondence, builder or waterproofing certificates, and any flood mitigation works completed on the property or in the local area by Council.</p>

      <p>Your agent should know how comparable flood-affected properties have sold in your area and be able to advise you on realistic price expectations. Overpricing a flood-affected property to leave room for negotiation is a poor strategy for the same reason it is in any market: it extends days on market and signals to buyers that you are not price-aware. A realistic, well-evidenced price point with full disclosure tends to produce cleaner, faster transactions than a strategy built on concealment or wishful pricing.</p>

